🔐 What is HTTPS?

HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure) is a secure version of HTTP used to transfer data between your browser and a website.

🧠 Simple Definition (Interview Style)

👉 HTTPS is a protocol that encrypts data between client and server to keep communication secure.

🌐 Easy Example

When you open a website like:

https://google.com
The 🔒 lock icon in the browser means the connection is secure.
🔑 How HTTPS works
Uses SSL/TLS encryption
Data is converted into a secret code (encrypted)
Only the server and client can understand it
⚙️ HTTPS vs HTTP
Feature	HTTP ❌	HTTPS ✅
Security	No	Yes (Encrypted)
Port	80	443
Data Safety	Unsafe	Safe
Example	http://	https://
🔐 Why HTTPS is important?
Protects passwords 🔑
Secures payment info 💳
Prevents hacking & data theft
Builds trust (🔒 symbol)
🚀 Real Example

When you log in to a website:

Without HTTPS → data can be stolen
With HTTPS → data is encrypted and safe
🎯 Short Answer (for interview)

👉 “HTTPS is a secure version of HTTP that uses SSL/TLS encryption to protect data during communication between client and server.”
